photos.Locality: Half Moon Bay SB--Venice Beach and Pilarcitos Creek Mouth
photos.Observation Details: Found by Alvaro Jaramillo.  Seen from bluffs at Venice Beach looking over Francis Creek mouth.  Adult.  Appearance much like a Western Gull, perhaps a tiny bit smaller, much like the Herring Gulls it was associating with - back darker and 'slaty' than Western.  Legs more of a bubble-gum red and appear short. giving the bird a sleaker, shorter look than Western.  Head is streaky, with fine streaks, especailly around eye - yellow iris, only notable in direct sun.  Bill much thinner than Western, more like a Herring, with a small gonydial bump and small red gonys patch.  Bill is pale at the base with some yellow at the tip - but overall this is the most distinguishing differentiator from Western.

photos.Locality: Pelagic. Island Packers. Leg 7. 33.60863 -119.66825. Bearing SSE
photos.Observation Details: The Wedge-rumped Storm-Petrel was discovered in photos of the large Black and Ashy Storm-Petrel flock at 12:39. Some may have seen the bird as it lifted up from the far-left side of the flock and several photographers discovered the bird in their images; most notably Aaron Maizlish and Larry Sansone. This bird was noticeable smaller than the other storm-petrels. The bird was black and appeared to be in heavy wing molt. A large triangular white rump patch extending almost to the end of the tail was evident, unlike the rump of a Townsend's. The bird also had a short thick bill, steep forehead, and no pronounced carpal bars. The deep wingbeats in the photos are also consistent with Wedge-rumped. Upon reviewing the photos, Steve Howell noted that the molting wings are consistent with Wedge-rumped at this season; this molt is not typical of Townsend’s at this season. The consensus among several of the leaders and other seabird experts that were consulted in the following days was that this individual was indeed a Wedge-rumped Storm-Petrel. This bird was in view for only a few seconds and was gone quickly as the flock dispersed.  This bird was seen 19 nautical miles NNW from San Nicolas island (GPS coordinates: 33,35,7.2240, 119,38,39.92399).
Distant

photos.Locality: Pelagic. Island Packers. Leg 7. 33.60863 -119.66825. Bearing SSE
photos.Observation Details: At approximately 12:37 as we were sneaking up on the big storm-petrel flock, a large storm-petrel quartered in towards the bow from the right. It was called out that “a close storm-petrel” was in front of the boat so those on the bow could get photos and identify it. The consensus of some in the bow was a dark-rumped Leach's, but they were troubled by some of the field marks. A dark-rumped chapmani Leach’s was trailing the bird in question so that may have caused some confusion. Those birds passed the bow quickly.  The bird was gone so fast as storm-petrels do and we were approaching the large flock so we were on to the next thing. Upon reviewing photos the following day, David Pereksta was alarmed when he saw the details of this bird and suspected it could be a Tristram's Storm-Petrel.  A robust-looking sooty-colored storm-petrel with pale back and rump, deeply forked tail, bright carpal bars, and contrastingly dark head. In addition, other photos show it apparently gliding on slightly bowed wings. The underside was uniformly dark including the underwings. The carpal bars were very pale at the base along the inner trailing edge of the wings, indicating a fresh juvenile. The primary shafts appeared bare, but this species has dark shafts that can reflect silvery under certain lighting conditions. Joel Barrett’s photos with the Leach’s in the same frame show a shocking size difference with the bird in question being much larger and more robust. The overwhelming consensus of seabird experts consulted is that the bird is a Tristram's Storm-Petrel.  This bird was seen 19 nautical miles NNW from San Nicolas island (GPS coordinates: 33,35,20.88000, 119,38,51.79200).

Small immature booby, about the same length as a Western Gull but noticeably slimmer and smaller in appearance.  Chest was creamy, with a brown belly, kind of the opposite of what I would expect in an imm. Brown Booby, with no sharp contrasts.   Bill had that long, flattened shape that I associate with Red-footed - mostly pink with some blue tones at the base.  Dark eye.  I've seen them in Polynesia, but don't have experience with the immature ones.    I never saw the feet, the bird was stationary for the 30+ minutes that we viewed it.   Found earlier today by Ryan Terrill, probably the same bird as reported by Josiah Clark as a "probable" Red-footed last week.

Young (1st/2nd year?) booby with cafe-latte colored chest, belly, scaps and darker primaries and tail - about the size of a cormorant but somewhat lighter.  Bill a fleshy dull pink color, notably bright red and extremely short legs.  Never moved while I was photographing it.  I believe this is 2nd city record.

Continuing on the main lawn with the Canada Geese.  First reported by Derek Heins.   Stocky egret that stayed in a "hunched" position most of the time I was watching, even while walking.  Short black legs - all white plumage, I could not pick out any orange on the back of head or wings that I association with Cattle Egrets.  Bill is thick, stocky - not like a Reddish Egret - appeared to be dull pink with a blackish tip.   Overall about the size of a Snowy Egret, maybe appears even smaller but that might just be the poor posture.

photos.Observation Details: Two hawks were flying north as I was arriving on the hill - heading over Mission Dolores.  One was an obvious RTHA, the second a small buteo that I immediately took to be a Broad-winged.  Tail had barring on both top and bottom.  Smaller compared to RTHA with elongated tail, and seemed to have shorter wings with definitive bulge.  In flight the top of the tail had wide dark bands (not in photo), and the belly was very white.  Was almost out of sight by the time I had my camera out, but I think the photos should be sufficient.    Expert opinion that this is actually a Cooper's Hawk.

Was almost out of sight by the time I had my camera out, but I think the photos should be sufficient.    Expert opinion that this is actually a Cooper's Hawk.
